6.2[Initial Implementation](#Initial-Implementation)\n- 6.3[Decisions Pending](#Decisions-Pending)\n\n# DevOps Transformation Scope - Build, Test, Release, Deploy\n\nBroadly speaking, DevOps represents the unification of development and operations practices into a continuous cycle of delivery and feedback. The lifecycle is visualised as an infinity loop, reflecting the continuous nature of modern software delivery. This initiative focuses on modernising the core delivery pipeline — the**Build**,**Test**,**Release**, and**Deploy**stages of the DevOps lifecycle.\n\nThe left side of the loop (Plan → Code → Build → Test) represents the**development**flow, while the right side (Release → Deploy → Operate → Monitor) represents the**operations**flow. Information flows continuously between both sides, with monitoring insights feeding back into planning.\n\nOpen image-20251203-021506.png![image-20251203-021506.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n\n## \nContinuous Integration (CI)\n\nCI is the practice of frequently merging code changes into a shared repository, where automated builds and tests validate each change. The goal is to detect integration issues early, when they are cheaper and easier to fix. CI typically covers the**Code**,**Build**, and**Test**stages.\n\n## Continuous Delivery/Deployment (CD)\n\nCD extends CI by automating the release process. Continuous Delivery ensures code is always in a deployable state; Continuous Deployment goes further by automatically releasing every validated change to production. CD covers the**Release**,**Deploy**,**Operate**, and**Monitor**stages.\n\n## DORA Metrics\n\nThe DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) metrics are the industry standard for measuring software delivery performance. They are collected across the Build, Test, Release, and Deploy stages and provide objective benchmarks for improvement.\n\n**Deployment Frequency**— How often code is deployed to production.\n\n**Lead Time for Changes**— Time from code commit to production deployment.\n\n**Change Failure Rate**— Percentage of deployments causing failures in production.\n\n**Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR)**— Time to restore service after an incident.\n\n## \nWhy These Four Stages?\n\nThese stages represent the automated heart of software delivery where we can achieve the greatest immediate impact on quality, speed, and reliability. They are the stages where DORA metrics are most directly measured and improved — and where automation delivers the highest return on investment.\n\n## What's Out of Scope (For Now)\n\n**Plan**and**Code**remain with existing tooling and processes.**Operate**and**Monitor**(the observability stack) are documented as a future phase — the groundwork is laid, but implementation follows once the delivery pipeline is stable.\n\n# \n**Jenkins to GitHub Actions**\n\nConvert the build pipeline from Jenkins to GitHub Actions, aligning with the strategic pillar of Modern Engineering Practices.\n\nOpen image-20251202-063504.png![image-20251202-063504.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n\n**Integration and Context**— The CI/CD pipeline lives in the same location as the code, pull requests, issues, and project management. This reduces context-switching and provides deep integration.\n\n**Pipeline as Code**— Workflow files are version-controlled within the repository, ensuring the pipeline definition stays in sync with the code. The declarative YAML format is easier for developers to read, understand, and modify.\n\n**Reduced Administrative Overhead**— Eliminates the necessity of maintaining, securing, or updating a separate CI server.\n\n**Dependency Management**— Integrating Dependabot to manage and maintain the currency of dependencies.\n\n## Runner Selection\n\nThe legacy C/C++ codebase requires RedHat 8, gcc-toolset-12, and sudo access for setuid binaries. This rules out GitHub-Hosted runners for the primary build. The following options are listed in order of preference.\n\n#### 1. AWS Self-Hosted Runner (Recommended)\n\nA persistent EC2 instance running the GitHub Actions runner agent.\n\n**How it works**— An EC2 instance runs the GitHub Actions runner as a service. The instance is pre-configured with RedHat 8, gcc-toolset-12, and all build dependencies. Jobs are picked up immediately with no startup delay.\n\n**Why first preference**— Can be set up relatively quickly using existing AWS infrastructure. Provides a template for an optimised runner configuration that can be refined over time. Full control over the environment means the legacy toolchain requirements (setuid binaries, specific compiler versions) are straightforward to satisfy.\n\n**Trade-offs**— Pays for idle time (~$70–150/mo), requires ongoing maintenance (patching, security updates). Suitable as the initial implementation while build patterns are established.\n\n### 2. Self-Hosted Ephemeral Runner\n\nEC2 instances spun up on-demand via Auto Scaling Groups or a controller.\n\n**How it works**— A controller listens for GitHub webhook events. When a job is queued, it launches a new EC2 instance from a pre-baked AMI containing the full build environment. The instance registers as a runner, executes the job, then terminates.\n\n**Why second preference**— Cost effective for variable workloads — pay only for actual build time (~$5–20/mo depending on volume). Clean environment for each build eliminates state pollution. Scales horizontally for parallel matrix builds.\n\n**Trade-offs**— Higher setup complexity. Requires maintaining AMIs and the controller infrastructure. Cold start delay of 30 seconds to 2 minutes per job.\n\n### 3. AWS CodeBuild\n\nFully managed build service integrated with GitHub Actions.\n\n**How it works**— GitHub Actions triggers CodeBuild via the`aws-actions/aws-codebuild-run-build`action. Builds run in a custom Docker image containing the RedHat 8 toolchain. No runner infrastructure to manage.\n\n**Why third preference**— AWS managed and templated, removing infrastructure overhead entirely. Most cost effective option with no idle costs and per-minute billing. Integrates with existing AWS accounts and IAM.\n\n**Trade-offs**— Build environment is containerised, which may complicate setuid binary requirements. Less flexibility than a full VM. 30–60 second startup time.\n\n### 4. GitHub-Hosted Runners\n\nGitHub-Hosted runners remain suitable for auxiliary tasks like linting, documentation builds, and notifications where the RedHat/gcc-toolset requirements do not apply.\n\n# **Static and Security Analysis**\n\n### Integrate pre-commit code analysis and quality assurance as part of the strategic initiative to Move Quality Left — catching problems at the earliest stage possible.\n\nWhy Two Layers?\n\nPre-commit hooks and server-side analysis serve complementary purposes. Local hooks provide instant feedback — developers see issues in seconds rather than waiting for a CI pipeline, keeping them in flow and preventing context-switching. However, local hooks can be bypassed (intentionally or accidentally), and some analysis is too slow or resource-intensive to run on every commit.\n\nServer-side checks act as a safety net. They enforce standards consistently regardless of individual developer setup, run deeper analysis that would disrupt local workflows, and provide an auditable record of code quality. The combination ensures speed where it matters (local) and rigour where it counts (server).\n\nOpen image-20251202-063946.png![image-20251202-063946.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n\n## Pre-Commit Hooks (Local)\n\nChecks that run locally and nearly instantaneously, designed to avoid disrupting the developer's workflow.\n\n**Linting**— Enforced format standardisation to catch stylistic errors and formatting issues, improving readability and reducing cognitive load during code reviews.\n\n**Nullify**— Early security and code quality scanning before code leaves the developer's machine.\n\n## Server-Side Analysis (On Push/PR)\n\n**Static Analysis**— Clang, Cppcheck, and GCC enhanced warnings to isolate potential bugs, security vulnerabilities, and anti-patterns in the legacy C codebase.\n\n**Secret Scanning**— Prevents developers from accidentally committing API keys, passwords, and private certificates into repository history.\n\n**Dependabot**— Automated dependency updates and vulnerability alerts.\n\n# **Extended & Add Pipelines**\n\nImplement Continuous Integration on Push and set up additional pipelines for comprehensive testing, nightly analysis, and weekly load profiling.\n\nOpen image-20251202-064531.png![image-20251202-064531.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n\n## QA Integration (On Push)\n\nExecutes a comprehensive set of automated tests on commit — unit tests, integration tests, and smoke tests. Includes checks for code quality and coverage (duplication, complexity).\n\n### Nightly Analysis\n\nRuns Clang static analyser or Infer using the highest level of time-consuming analysis settings to surface complex bugs. Integrates AccelQ test automation for end-to-end testing.\n\n### Weekly Profiling\n\nRuns the VLab Virtual User Simulator (VUT) as a load-generation tool executing scenarios with real-world load numbers. Requires an in-cloud setup capable of running up to 2000 separate virtual users. Crucial for validating performance-sensitive changes like the segfile removal initiative.\n\n### Pre-Release Testing\n\nOn-demand security-focused review using Flawfinder as part of the release checklist.\n\n# **Observability Stack**\n\nImprove observability and reduce Mean Time to Restore (MTTR) for production incidents. This section reflects discovery findings — details will evolve as decisions are confirmed.\n\n### Context\n\nCurrent monitoring is fragmented across bespoke scripts, spreadsheets, and partial Prometheus deployment. DataDog is being phased out due to cost. No unified platform exists across AWS and on-premises environments, and support relies on reactive dashboard watching rather than proactive alerting.\n\nThe Segfile Removal team completed a successful OpenTelemetry proof of concept, validating the instrumentation approach for the LIMS C codebase. This resolves the APM capability gap and confirms OpenTelemetry as the recommended path forward.\n\nOpen image-20251203-042445.png![image-20251203-042445.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n\n### Initial Implementation\n\n**OpenTelemetry Instrumentation**— Instrument applications using the OpenTelemetry SDK, leveraging the Segfile Removal team POC as the reference implementation. Provides correlated metrics, traces, and logs.\n\n**Platform Infrastructure**— Platform team deploys OpenTelemetry Collector, Prometheus, Grafana, Grafana Tempo (tracing), and Grafana Loki (logs).\n\n**Dashboards**— Create one operations dashboard and one application monitoring dashboard to demonstrate patterns and provide immediate operational value.\n\n**Alerting Integration**— Configure Grafana alerting to Jira Service Management (JSM) as the company-wide standard.\n\n**Blueprint and Training**— Author documentation covering instrumentation, dashboard creation, alert configuration, and SLO/SLA definition. Deliver hands-on training to enable engineers to instrument applications independently.\n\n### Decisions Pending\n\n**Environment Scope**— V1 may focus on AWS only (simpler, faster) or include on-premises (proves model across both environments but adds firewall complexity).\n\n**Stack Approval**— CTO confirmation of the full observability stack as the company-wide solution.\n\n**Metrics Prioritisation**— Discovery session with support and engineering to identify highest-value metrics for the pilot.\n\n## Related content\n\nMore infoCollapse[Engineering Practice Uplift -
